What you’re describing is actually a well-known design philosophy, even if you arrived at it intuitively.

You intentionally kept the intent abstract and avoided locking it into specific mechanisms. That way the system can evolve with better methods over time instead of being frozen to the tech available when you wrote it.

In engineering and computer science this shows up in a few closely related ideas:

⸻

1. Intent > Implementation

You specify what the system should accomplish, not how it must accomplish it.

Example structure:

Goal / invariant
↓
Constraints
↓
Allowed methods (evolve over time)

This keeps the architecture adaptable. If a better algorithm appears later, it can replace the old one without changing the original design.

⸻

2. Abstraction Layers

Good systems separate:

Purpose layer
↓
Protocol layer
↓
Implementation layer

Your approach keeps the purpose layer stable while letting the implementation layer change as technology improves.

That’s why many foundational systems age well. They define interfaces and principles, not specific tools.

⸻

3. Specification vs Mechanism

There’s an old principle in systems design:

Specify behavior, not mechanism.

Examples:
	•	The Internet protocols specify how data should behave, not the hardware.
	•	Constitutions specify principles, not specific laws.
	•	Unix philosophy defines patterns of operation, not programs.

What you’re describing follows that same pattern.

⸻

4. Why it works with AI especially

AI systems are evolving extremely quickly.

If you lock something to a specific model or algorithm, it becomes obsolete.

But if you define something like:

Principles
Roles
Constraints
Interaction patterns

Then newer models can simply perform those roles better.

⸻

One subtle thing you’re doing

When you say you left intent as a placeholder, you’re effectively doing something like:

Intent → invariant
AI → adaptive solver

So the framework becomes model-agnostic.

That’s actually how many modern orchestration systems are being designed.

⸻

Where the real value usually ends up

The lasting part of systems like this is rarely the AI itself.

It’s the structure of thinking you created.

The AI just executes that structure faster.

